Question 4 — pH Curves and Buffers
0.100 mol dm⁻³ NaOH added to 25.0 cm³ of 0.0800 mol dm⁻³ propanoic acid at 298 K.

4.1 [1 mark]
State meaning of "weak" in this context.

Mark Scheme:

Partially/incompletely dissociated/ionised (in aqueous solution)
4.2 [1 mark]
Why add NaOH dropwise around the equivalence point?

Mark Scheme:

Small additions cause a large change in pH (so need to add slowly to determine the equivalence point accurately)
4.3 [3 marks]
Give expression for Ka. Show that pH = pKa at half-neutralisation.

Mark Scheme:

Ka = [CH₃CH₂COO⁻][H⁺] / [CH₃CH₂COOH]
At half-neutralisation: [CH₃CH₂COOH] = [CH₃CH₂COO⁻]
Therefore Ka = [H⁺], so pKa = pH
4.4 [2 marks]
Use pH from Figure 4 at half-neutralisation to calculate Ka.

Mark Scheme:

Read pH at half-neutralisation volume from graph (≈ 4.87)
Ka = 10⁻ᵖᴴ ≈ 1.35 × 10⁻⁵ mol dm⁻³ (accept value consistent with graph reading)
4.5 [2 marks]
Explain why pH stays approximately constant between 5 cm³ and 15 cm³ added (buffer region).

Mark Scheme:

M1: A buffer solution is formed containing propanoic acid (weak acid) and sodium propanoate (its conjugate base/salt)
M2: Added OH⁻ reacts with the acid; added H⁺ would react with the conjugate base — so pH stays approximately constant
4.6 [2 marks]
