Question 5 — Transition Metal Complexes and Colorimetry
5.1 [6 marks]
Explain why some complexes are coloured, list factors affecting colour, and describe how colorimetry determines concentration.

Mark Scheme (Indicative Content):

d orbitals split into two sets of different energies (in the presence of ligands)
Light is absorbed to promote an electron from a lower d orbital to a higher d orbital
The colour observed is the complementary colour to the wavelength absorbed
Factors affecting colour: type of ligand / coordination number / oxidation state of the metal ion
Colorimetry: make solutions of known concentration → measure absorbance → plot calibration curve (absorbance vs concentration) → measure absorbance of unknown → read concentration from graph
Zero the colorimeter with distilled water / appropriate solvent
Use an appropriate filter (complementary colour)
5.2 [3 marks]
Use peak wavelength from visible spectrum of [Cu(H₂O)₆]²⁺ to calculate the change in energy of an electron. (h = 6.63 × 10⁻³⁴ J s, c = 3.00 × 10⁸ m s⁻¹)

Mark Scheme:

M1: Read wavelength from graph (≈ 800 nm = 800 × 10⁻⁹ m)
M2: E = hc/λ = (6.63 × 10⁻³⁴ × 3.00 × 10⁸) / (800 × 10⁻⁹)
M3: E ≈ 2.49 × 10⁻¹⁹ J (accept value consistent with graph reading)
